<font color="#FF0000">WE ARE HOME</font><br>
<tt>Mon Oct 13 18:25:22 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Cook and Tom,<br><br>
I have several Marines, which either work for me or team with my group daily.  Last &quot;Memorial Day&quot; one of the more strait laced serious marines came up to me gave me a hug and said &quot;Welcome Home&quot;.  I sat astonished and he dismayed that I didn't have the foggiest idea what had happened.  I felt both elated for the experience somehow and ashamed that I had missed out on the meaning.<br><br>
The last time I had those exact feelings is when my co-pilot was telling the other new guys in country that I was the 'Old Man&quot;.  When referred to as the &quot;Old Man&quot; you were being paid a compliment of the highest level.  It went along with being one of the few flight or wave leads.  A right of passage which wasn't connected to rank, but trust.<br><br>
They would look to you for guidance on both social behavior and conduct on each mission.  I had the honor to mold many young men into fine warriors.  I occasionally get a visit from them to say hello.<br><br>
Cook you may find that your exploits are the conversation of some of the new warriors.  I was told that men who have never met me tell stories about me.  I have been close to a few but did not identify myself.  I like their versions better than mine.<br><br>
We are home.  The warriors of today hold a special place for us.  They make you feel welcome.  Warriors have always been an isolated group whose strength is gained from among their ranks.  Manner, training, and uniform to separate us from society and bind us into a group.  Armies for thousands of years have done this.  Society has been conditioned to see us separate and apart. Maybe we ask too much from the rank and file to understand the complexity of who or what we are.  They can't look us in the face or acknowledge us because of their shame not ours.  They fear us at times; I have seen it in their eyes.<br><br>
If we ask others to accept us then we must accept ourselves.  Some of us have and others with PTSD are struggling with their own acceptance.  We do not need to look to others for what we can give ourselves.<br><br>
Peace<br>

